# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vllm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:vllm/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:vllm/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In the field of artificial intelligence, an **inference engine** is a software component of an intelligent system that applies logical rules to the knowledge base to deduce new information.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The first inference engines were components of expert systems.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The typical expert system consisted of a knowledge base and an inference engine.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The knowledge base stored facts about the world.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The inference engine applied logical rules to the knowledge base and deduced new knowledge.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] This process would iterate as each new fact in the knowledge base could trigger additional rules in the inference engine.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Inference engines work primarily in one of two modes either special rule or facts: forward chaining and backward chaining.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Forward chaining starts with the known facts and asserts new facts.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Backward chaining starts with goals, and works backward to determine what facts must be asserted so that the goals can be achieved.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Additionally, the concept of 'inference' has expanded to include the process through which trained neural networks generate predictions or decisions.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In this context, an 'inference engine' could refer to the specific part of the system, or even the hardware, that executes these operations.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] This type of inference plays a crucial role in various applications, including (but not limited to) image recognition, natural language processing, and autonomous vehicles.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The inference phase in these applications is typically characterized by a high volume of data inputs and real-time processing requirements.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The logic that an inference engine uses is typically represented as IF-THEN rules.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The general format of such rules is IF <logical expression> THEN <logical expression>.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Prior to the development of expert systems and inference engines, artificial intelligence researchers focused on more powerful theorem prover environments that offered much fuller implementations of first-order logic.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] For example, general statements that included universal quantification (for all X some statement is true) and existential quantification (there exists some X such that some statement is true).
[src:vllm/inference-engine] What researchers discovered is that the power of these theorem-proving environments was also their drawback.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Back in 1965, it was far too easy to create logical expressions that could take an indeterminate or even infinite time to terminate.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] For example, it is common in universal quantification to make statements over an infinite set such as the set of all natural numbers.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Such statements are perfectly reasonable and even required in mathematical proofs but when included in an automated theorem prover executing on a computer may cause the computer to fall into an infinite loop.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Focusing on IF-THEN statements (what logicians call *modus ponens*) still gave developers a very powerful general mechanism to represent logic, but one that could be used efficiently with computational resources.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] What is more, there is some psychological research that indicates humans also tend to favor IF-THEN representations when storing complex knowledge.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] A simple example of *modus ponens* often used in introductory logic books is "If you are human then you are mortal".
[src:vllm/inference-engine] A trivial example of how this rule would be used in an inference engine is as follows.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In *forward chaining*, the inference engine would find any facts in the knowledge base that matched Human(x) and for each fact it found would add the new information Mortal(x) to the knowledge base.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] So if it found an object called Socrates that was human it would deduce that Socrates was mortal.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In *backward chaining*, the system would be given a goal, e.g. answer the question is Socrates mortal?
[src:vllm/inference-engine] It would search through the knowledge base and determine if Socrates was human and, if so, would assert he is also mortal.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] However, in backward chaining a common technique was to integrate the inference engine with a user interface.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In that way, rather than simply being automated the system could now be interactive.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In this trivial example, if the system was given the goal to answer the question if Socrates was mortal and it didn't yet know if he was human, it would generate a window to ask the user the question "Is Socrates human?" and would then use that information accordingly.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] This innovation of integrating the inference engine with a user interface led to the second early advancement of expert systems: explanation capabilities.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The explicit representation of knowledge as rules rather than code made it possible to generate explanations to users: both explanations in real time and after the fact.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] At first these explanations were not much different than the standard debugging information that developers deal with when debugging any system.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] However, an active area of research was utilizing natural language technology to ask, understand, and generate questions and explanations using natural languages rather than computer formalisms.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] An inference engine cycles through three sequential steps: *match rules*, *select rules*, and *execute rules*.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The execution of the rules will often result in new facts or goals being added to the knowledge base, which will trigger the cycle to repeat.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] This cycle continues until no new rules can be matched.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In the first step, *match rules*, the inference engine finds all of the rules that are triggered by the current contents of the knowledge base.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In forward chaining, the engine looks for rules where the antecedent (left hand side) matches some fact in the knowledge base.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In backward chaining, the engine looks for antecedents that can satisfy one of the current goals.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In the second step, *select rules*, the inference engine prioritizes the various rules that were matched to determine the order to execute them.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] In the final step, *execute rules*, the engine executes each matched rule in the order determined in step two and then iterates back to step one again.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The cycle continues until no new rules are matched.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Early inference engines focused primarily on forward chaining.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] These systems were usually implemented in the Lisp programming language.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Lisp was a frequent platform for early AI research due to its strong capability to do symbolic manipulation.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Also, as an interpreted language it offered productive development environments appropriate to debugging complex programs.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] A necessary consequence of these benefits was that Lisp programs tended to be slower and less robust than compiled languages of the time such as C.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] A common approach in these early days was to take an expert system application and repackage the inference engine used for that system as a re-usable tool other researchers could use for the development of other expert systems.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] For example, MYCIN was an early expert system for medical diagnosis and EMYCIN was an inference engine extrapolated from MYCIN and made available for other researchers.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] As expert systems moved from research prototypes to deployed systems there was more focus on issues such as speed and robustness.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] One of the first and most popular forward chaining engines was OPS5, which used the Rete algorithm to optimize the efficiency of rule firing.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Another very popular technology that was developed was the Prolog logic programming language.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] Prolog focused primarily on backward chaining and also featured various commercial versions and optimizations for efficiency and robustness.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] As expert systems prompted significant interest from the business world, various companies, many of them started or guided by prominent AI researchers created productized versions of inference engines.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] For example, Intellicorp was initially guided by Edward Feigenbaum.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] These inference engine products were also often developed in Lisp at first.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] However, demands for more affordable and commercially viable platforms eventually made personal computer platforms very popular.
[src:vllm/inference-engine] ClipsRules and RefPerSys (inspired by CAIA and the work of Jacques Pitrat).
[src:vllm/inference-engine] The Frama-C static source code analyzer also uses some inference engine techniques.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:vllm/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:vllm/transformer-deep-learning-architecture-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:vllm/vllm] vLLM was introduced in 2023 by researchers affiliated with the Sky Computing Lab at UC Berkeley.
[src:vllm/vllm] Its core ideas were described in the 2023 paper *Efficient Memory Management for Large Language Model Serving with PagedAttention*, which presented the system as a high-throughput and memory-efficient serving engine for large language models.
[src:vllm/vllm] According to a project maintainer, the "v" in vLLM originally referred to "virtual", inspired by virtual memory.
[src:vllm/vllm] PyTorch's project page states that the University of California, Berkeley contributed vLLM to the Linux Foundation in July 2024.
[src:vllm/vllm] In 2025, the PyTorch Foundation announced that vLLM had become a Foundation-hosted project.
[src:vllm/vllm] In January 2026, *TechCrunch* reported that the creators of vLLM had launched the startup Inferact to commercialize the project, raising $150 million in seed funding.
[src:vllm/vllm] According to its 2023 paper, vLLM was designed to improve the efficiency of large language model serving by reducing memory waste in the key–value cache used during transformer inference.
[src:vllm/vllm] The paper introduced *PagedAttention*, an algorithm inspired by virtual memory and paging techniques in operating systems, and described vLLM as using block-level memory management and request scheduling to increase throughput while maintaining similar latency.
[src:vllm/vllm] The project documentation and repository describe support for continuous batching, chunked prefill, speculative decoding, prefix caching, quantization, and multiple forms of distributed inference.
[src:vllm/vllm] PyTorch has described vLLM as a high-throughput, memory-efficient inference and serving engine that supports a range of hardware back ends, including NVIDIA and AMD GPUs, Google TPUs, AWS Trainium, and Intel processors.
